This project explores the application of various statistical learning and machine learning techniques to detect fraudulent credit card transactions.
Using a real-world dataset from Kaggle, the goal is to build and evaluate models that can identify fraud in highly imbalanced data settings.

ğŸ“Š Dataset

The dataset comes from Kaggle and contains real transactions made by credit card holders over two days in September 2013, provided by Europay, MasterCard, and Visa.
Key characteristics:

284,807 total transactions

492 fraudulent cases (highly imbalanced)

Features are primarily anonymized PCA components (V1, V2, ..., V28)

Includes Time, Amount, and a binary Class indicating fraud (1) or not (0)

ğŸ¯ Project Objectives

Explore and clean the transaction dataset

Handle class imbalance using techniques such as:

Oversampling (SMOTE)

Undersampling

Stratified splitting

Apply multiple statistical learning and machine learning models, such as:

Logistic Regression

Decision Trees

Random Forests

Gradient Boosting

Support Vector Machines

Neural Networks

Compare model performance using metrics appropriate for imbalanced classification:

Precision, Recall, F1-score

ROCâ€“AUC

